data.title: Community Gardens
data.excerpt: I never managed a plot in a community garden. I joined a waitlist once, contacted the email list a few times, but never actually had one of those raised beds to call my own. I appreciated seeing them, championed their cause, stared at them admiringly through chain-linked fences, but they always remained an arms reach away.

children.text: I never managed a plot in a community garden. I joined a waitlist once, contacted the email list a few times, but never actually had one of those raised beds to call my own. I appreciated seeing them, championed their cause, stared at them admiringly through chain-linked fences, but they always remained an arms reach away.

It turns out it just wasnt the right community garden for me. Community Gardens can be individual plots, but they can also be collaborative, a communal garden shared with the community. The goal being to get more people involved, people that wouldnt have gardened at all on their own, but bring their own value to the garden, a vitality through diversity in skillset, backgrounds, hobbies, culture. Whats more community than that?

Lets face it, when that tomato or cucumber plant reaches its peak harvest, this is not a bounty for a single person, or even a single family. Theres only so much squash soup you can fit in your freezer. More hands planting, more hands harvesting, and the more humans being fed. These principles are the bedrock of urban agriculture.

There are many ways to make this style of community gardening work. After a few years of managing one Ive found that hosting regular volunteer work days seems to be best. Having simple text blasts about them, and planning the planting or creative projects in monthly meetings. What is the vision for the land? Is it to grow the most amount of food as possible? Or is it to be as passive as possible, and slowly work towards a hands-off food forest?

children.text: Whenever I get to witness the lifecycle of a fruit or plant at various stages in one sitting I feel closer to it. I love berries. Blackberries is now that Im thinking and writing about it the first thing that I ever foraged! I grew up with blackberries in a path in my neighborhood and have fond memories of finding ripe berries and feeling safe to snack on them to my heart's content. But if there werent ripe berries to be seen then it was an out of sight out of mind plant, camouflaged in green-ness.

Now that I understand the life cycle of fruit I can begin to really appreciate the flowers for more than their beauty, but for their utility. Their complex presence that turns them from pretty stage, to ugly stage, to bounty stage. PUB? Nah thats weird. But here we have the blackberry in almost all of its forms (ableit no ripe ones), adding splendor to my morning hike.

Those closed bulbs surrounding the flower to berry stages I was happy to hear are called the popcorn stage of the blackberry, its the stage before the flower blooms for the first time. The flower to fruit stage depends on the weather, mainly the warm, and takes between 35-60 days. Who knows, maybe with my daily blogging tracking the dates for how long it takes here in Oakland is a possibility, albeit a longshot ;)

My favorite part about viewing this blackberry was seeing how each little hair, each pistil, in the center forms a little fruit bulb at its base, creating an aggregate fruit. Aggregate fruit is where the fruit is created from multiple ovaries (ovaries are at the base of the pistil), and as they mature they fuse together into a singular appearing fruit,  in contrast to simple fruits from a single ovary, like grapes, blueberries, bananas etcThe magic of nature in the form of fertilization and germination. Thank your pollinators!

children.text: Watching Canadian geese zoom under the bridge, I found myself captivated by one goose eating seaweed. I wondered, is that seaweed safe for it to consume? How beautiful it is that this species can thrive on the bounty of seaweed created by our world. So many animals live off this abundance, a simple by-product of sunlight and water.

My species, humans, has been part of the destruction of these beautiful life forms that have existed far longer than we have. We came along and threatened to ruin it all! But it's worth considering that we might be on an upswing now. We've waned as far as we can, and now we've begun the great waxing that will carry our humanity and its connection with all life well into the future.

There have always been groups dedicated to helping what we're hurting. We, as humanity, can't watch the harm and do nothing - that isn't who we are. In fact, harming ourselves by damaging the environment isn't something we'll take lightly. We're the cause of our own pain, and there's only so long we'll endure it. Some have already devoted their entire lives to this cause, but we don't need that from everyone. We just need committed, consistent, imperfect action from everyone to fully swing the rubber band of natural balance back to thriving.

Before we stop swinging in the right direction, we will have reached such abundance, such a deep connection with nature and ourselves within it, that the natural balance will lead us to the next stage of life's evolution. A synergy of biodiversity and clean food abundance will emerge. It would take a meteor to set us back from this path.

children.text: Across cultures, from German sauerkraut to Korean kimchi, cabbage has been a cornerstone of fermented foods. Now that I have a few growing in my garden, and I recently dug into the benefits in a herbalism course, I wanted to spend some time digging into this unassuming vegetable.

Cabbage's high water content and sturdy cell walls create an ideal environment for fermentation. The process involves a fascinating succession of microorganisms: starting with Enterobacteriaceae, transitioning to Leuconostoc species, and finishing with acid-loving Lactobacillus. Were very lucky Lactobacillus ends up on top here, as theres very few probiotics better for our gut and digestive system.

Rich in vitamins, minerals, and natural sugars, cabbage provides excellent nutrition for both the fermenting bacteria and the humans who consume the final product. This nutritional profile likely contributed to its widespread adoption as a fermentation staple.

In a recent herbalism class, I experienced firsthand the versatility of cabbage fermentation. We made sauerkraut, but with a twist  incorporating various herbs into the mix. This approach not only enhanced the flavor but also demonstrated how fermentation can be used to extract and preserve the benefits of herbs. The resulting sauerkraut became a potent blend of probiotic goodness and herbal nutrition, allowing me to have one more way of accessing the goodness of herbs like plantain and my favorite herb, stinging nettles.

The global prevalence of fermented cabbage dishes raises intriguing questions about parallel cultural innovations. Knowing how many advancements we've had in food since the age of the internet, it's nice to see how the most traditional forms of food maintain relevance. Cabbage continues to offer insights into the complex relationships between plants, microbes, and human health. Also, you can keep it in your fridge for like a year, so thats cool too.

children.text: Public gardens are vibrant community spaces where people can relax, read, observe nature, and watch fruits and vegetables ripen. However, many aren't aware these gardens are open to all. To address this, we've found a simple yet effective solution: a community notice board.

A well-placed community board serves as the cornerstone of any shared space. It's more than just a place for announcements; it's an invitation to engage. Here, visitors can learn about the garden, leave notes for others, seek help finding lost pets, or advertise local businesses. Essentially, it's a beacon that says, "This space is for you. Please, enjoy it!"

Creating our garden's board was an exercise in resourcefulness and community spirit. I repurposed spare wood from under my house for the main structure. The 4x4 post came from the real estate company that had previously marketed the property - they kindly left it for our garden projects. As a zero-waste advocate, I initially planned to cover the board with wine corks I'd been collecting. However, my years-long collection fell short of what we needed.

The solution? We used the partially completed board to ask for cork donations! This request revealed I wasn't the only cork hoarder in the neighborhood. It also highlighted my relatively modest wine consumption compared to some community members - a relief, given that some of our garden co-founders don't drink at all.

The community's response was heartening. Not only did we receive enough corks to complete the board, but volunteers also stepped up to help with the time-consuming task of gluing them in place. It was a perfect demonstration of how a simple project can bring people together and strengthen community bonds.

This experience underscores the power of community initiatives. A community board is more than just a functional object; it's a symbol of shared space and collective effort. It invites participation, fosters communication, and turns a public garden into a true community hub.

children.text: Cast your mind back with me to about 8 or 9 years ago. I had just moved to Sacramento and was falling head over heels for picking oranges. It was my first time living somewhere with such an incredible, year-round display of fruitbright orbs beaming like perpetual Christmas ornaments. There didn't seem to be a season when these vibrant colors weren't popping against a lush green backdrop. Lemons, loquats, kumquatsthe abundance was staggering!

I can't quite recall how I stumbled upon the group that was actually doing something about this bounty, but there they were: Harvest Sacramento, an initiative of Soil Born Farms. They were ensuring all this rich life hanging from trees was picked, shared, and delivered to food banks. Their approach was educational, well-managed, and impressively organized.

When I left Sacramento, I was determined to share this practice of group harvesting with others. But as often happens when moving cities, life caught up with me. My grand plans dwindled to personal foraging and fruit tree tracking (using the Map Marker app). The bounty in my new home was equally impressive, but organizing around it seemed to require more time and effort than I could muster. So, reluctantly, I let the idea go.

Fast forward to now. As I'm building tools to help organize people, I realize my old dream of community harvests is becoming a much more tangible reality. In fact, I recently organized a mini-harvest for my backyard plum tree. This is something I can plan for, organize around, and grow with. With the right technology behind it, group harvests can be done even more effectively and in a more customized way than Harvest Sacramento's approach.
Also, what a fun and worthwhile problem to solve!

children.text: Rose hips have long been on my radar, their medicinal value etched in my memory from years ago when I purchased dried rose hips to make tea for a partner struggling with chronic health issues. Today, these vibrant little fruits made an unexpected comeback in my life, arriving with perfect timing and ripe for experimentation.

This morning brought two significant events: the news of my wife's positive COVID test, and an impromptu harvest during my dog walk. Before learning about my wife's condition, I had stumbled upon a bush adorned with these bright, beautiful, and juicy rose hips. Instinctively, I plucked a handful off their stems and tucked them into my pocket, not yet knowing how fortuitous this find would be.

Eager to put my bounty to use, I delved into some quick research. To my surprise, I discovered that rose hips are most potent when fresh - a fact that challenged my usual penchant for dehydrating herbs and fruits. This knowledge, along with a sick partner, inspired me to embark on creating my first-ever fresh rose hip tea.

Embracing this learning opportunity, I gently mashed the rose hips before steeping, aiming to maximize their surface area and coax out more of the beneficial compounds from the flesh. I poured 200-degree water over the crushed fruits and, following my research, let them steep for 8 minutes. Curiosity led me to extend this to 15 minutes, resulting in a noticeably deeper, richer hue.

The final product was a visual delight - tiny red sparkles dancing in the white porcelain cup, reminiscent of a mystical elixir. Its light, sweet taste carried an energetic quality, evoking thoughts of nature's own immunity booster.

As my wife sipped this homemade remedy, I couldn't help but marvel at the timing. In a moment when immunity support felt more crucial than ever, nature had provided exactly what we needed, right in our own neighborhood. I have such gratitude for the healing power of fresh, local botanicals.

children.text: Hey gardeners! I'm excited to share a new feature I'm building for Garden Steward: Task Instructions. Let me break it down for you.
Some garden tasks require all hands on deck and a lot of know-how. Take watering, for example. It's not just about turning on a hose. You need to:
Find the spigot on a specific property
Unlock it with a key
Water all plants, especially the young ones
Fill up barrels (with some handy tips)
Use the right hose nozzle settings
Check on things across the street
And that's just for watering! Other tasks can be just as complex. Here's where Task Instructions come in.
Here's how it works:
Get assigned a task in the app
Receive detailed instructions
Read and tap "Agree" before starting
If you can't complete it, easily hand it off to another volunteer
The key is having this knowledge at your fingertips. Every time a task is reassigned, the new volunteer gets notified of any updates they need to acknowledge.
Why This Matters

Our goal is to streamline garden involvement. It's not always practical to provide hands-on training for every task. Task Instructions allow us to mentor volunteers remotely before they take on new assignments.

This feature will help more people get involved in the garden efficiently. It's about making our community garden more accessible, getting the most amount of the community involved. Educated volunteers is the key to a successful garden, we can do a whole lot of great work together ,with a little instruction.

data.title: Yerba Santa
data.description: An aromatic evergreen shrub native to California and Oregon. Also known as Mountain Balm or Bear's Weed, it grows up to 3-4 meters tall with long, narrow leaves and clusters of lavender or white flowers. Traditionally used by Native Americans for respiratory ailments and as a general tonic, Yerba Santa (meaning "holy herb" in Spanish) is still used in herbal medicine and as a flavoring agent in some foods and beverages.
data.sun_detail: enjoys plenty of sun, or partial shade
data.magic: Great for setting boundaries. Yerba Santa has been used by various groups for benefiting love, purification, growth, empowerment, and beauty.
